&gt;In article &lt;353@nisca.ircc.ohio-state.edu&gt; bernstei@hpuxa.ircc.ohio-state.edu (Dan Bernstein) writes:
&gt;   As a pilot project, we are going to make available to the Internet
&gt;   a hosts table.
&gt;
&gt;   Sites with reliable name server access should not need this table.

Actually, name servers don't help much with some questions that a host table is
good for.  Like ``What is the NIC's name?'' and ``There's some host called
QUABBIN something something and what is the whole name?''.  I wonder if the new
host table will help us answer the question ``Somebody's name server is putting
out a host name with a comma (,) in it'' that was the subject of a few notes
earlier.  Come to think of it, I'd like to know if there are any wierd
characters floating around the DNS.

Such questions could be easier asked of some sort of server that searches a
host table, rather than giving you the whole table to search.  Also, that
server could incrementally maintain its database.  But I don't see anyone
RFCing such a service.

Dan

